<subSubSection pageId="89" pageNumber="147" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="89.[1379,2593,2017,3194]" pageId="89" pageNumber="147">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1382,1647,2571,2604]" pageId="89" pageNumber="147">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Green coconuts and inflorescences probably contributed to diets of OntongJava Flying Fox after native vegetation was removed from the 1950s onward, butits rarity might indicate a preference for previously existing native flora.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="89" pageNumber="147" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="89.[1379,2593,2017,3194]" pageId="89" pageNumber="147">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1381,1516,2689,2722]" pageId="89" pageNumber="147">Breeding.</emphasis>
Two of three female Ontong 
<collectingRegion box="[1961,2022,2689,2722]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="89" pageNumber="147">Java</collectingRegion>
Flying Foxes captured in August were pregnant with embryos weighing 
<quantity box="[1854,1912,2727,2760]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.0" pageId="89" pageNumber="147" unit="g" value="20.0">20 g</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[1984,2044,2727,2760]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.9" pageId="89" pageNumber="147" unit="g" value="29.0">29 g</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
